{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5152","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:29 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:29 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">In a more formal register, this nominalizer is pronounced <em>(n)khen</em>,<a href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> whereas in conversation it is usually pronounced as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངན་</span>, and even <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཉན་</span>. The verb to which it is attached takes the present-future.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུ་མཁན་</span> But not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུས་མཁན་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཟ་མཁན་</span> But not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཟས་མཁན་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལྟ་མཁན་</span> But not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བལྟས་མཁན་ </span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Like other nominalizers, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མཁན་</span> can form nominal clauses as well as relative clauses. This nominalizer prototypically indicates the <strong>agent </strong>of the verbal action, but also extends to the subject of transitive verbs and even (in most cases) to the subject of intransitive verbs.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འབྲི་མཁན་</span> “The person who writes,” “the writer”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུ་མཁན་</span> “The person who is speaking,” “the speaker”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཟ་མཁན་</span> “The person who is eating”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཚོང་མཁན་</span> “The person who is selling,” “the vendor”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྨི་ལམ་བཏང་མཁན་</span> “The dreamer”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཉལ་མཁན་</span> “The person who is sleeping,” “the sleeper”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Formulations with <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མཁན་</span> may sometimes be translated by terms for agents in European languages. In English, the suffix <em>–er</em> or the name of a profession often best conveys the sense of this nominalizer.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་བག་ལེབ་བཟོ་མཁན་རེད།</span> “He’s a baker.” (Literally: “He’s a bread-maker”) </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་རང་ཚོའི་གྲོགས་པོ་རྒྱ་མི་དེ་གློག་བརྙན་བཟོ་མཁན་རེད།</span> “Our Chinese friend is a film-maker.” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཐ་མག་འཐེན་མཁན་འདི་སུ་རེད།</span> “Who’s the person who’s smoking?” Or, “Who’s the smoker?”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མོ་ཊ་ནག་པོ་ཡོད་མཁན་དེ་རྫོང་དཔོན་གཅིག་རེད།</span> “The person who has the black car is the mayor of a district.” Or, “The owner of the black car is....”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">In certain cases, verbs that are nominalized with <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མཁན་</span> are practically the same as conjugated verbs. For example, the sentence: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ཡའི་(ཡང་)འགྲོ་མཁན་ཡིན།</span> “I’m also going,” which literally means: “I’m also a goer” is similar to: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ཡའི་(ཡང་)འགྲོ་གི་ཡིན།</span>.</p> <hr size=\"1\" /> <p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]</a> The nasal (<em>n</em>) that is noted here is a velar nasal (a nasal homorganic with the follow­ing consonant). This nasal, which is preserved in Tibetan spelling, is the source of two current pronunciations: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངན་</span> (a velar nasal) and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཉན་</span> (a palatal nasal). As far as the written form is concerned, in my discussions I retain the traditional spelling <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མཁན་</span>, since <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངན་</span> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཉན་</span> never appear in writing.</p>","title":""}]}
